      <title>Paths &amp; Managing Resources</title>
      <link>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc210/11-file-system/06-python/01-resources/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ksu-cs-textbooks.github.io/cc210/11-file-system/06-python/01-resources/</guid>
      <description>Path vs File objects In Python 2, the file system was accessed using a variety of functions built into several modules: sys, os, glob, shutil are some of the more common. The standard way to open a file was with the built-in function open(&amp;lt;str&amp;gt;).
a = open(&amp;#39;myTest.txt&amp;#39;) print (type(a)) #&amp;lt;type &amp;#39;file&amp;#39;&amp;gt; Which attempted to open the file represented by the string and returns a file-object. File-objects could be read, written to and searched.</description>
